match the rule's description: a broad closure with limited exceptions (daylight-only operations under approval). The rule's wording says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure... will not disqualify such a closure.\" So even with some airports open under restrictions, this is still a qualified major closure.\n\nTherefore, the vote should be \"demonstrated\" because the evidence shows a broad closure in the western Tehran FIR region with permissible exceptions, meeting the rule's criteria. The rationale needs to be concise: mention the raw NOTAM confirming the closure with specific exceptions that fit under allowed limited exceptions.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"The raw NOTAM text confirms a broad closure of western Tehran FIR with specific exceptions operating under limited daylight hours and fresh approval requirements, which meets the rule's definition of a major closure with permissible limited exceptions."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":19120,"output":559,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19679,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782830095287,"responseId":"gen-1782830095-7BTab7rPHwrQU3N3EQ2g","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, the user provided a detailed case scenario where I need to act as council member C1 for a specific arbitration case. Let me go through the steps they mentioned.\n\nFirst, the task was to use the MCP tool to call AAR tools with the correct format. The initial step was to call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` with empty args. The response showed \"state: ready\", so then I needed to read the prompt and other details to decide on the vote.\n\nThe prompt included a proposition about whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by May 24, 2026. The rule states a \"major closure\" must be a broad closure of flights in Iranian airspace or a major region, excluding limited partial closures but allowing limited exceptions for pre-approved flights.\n\nLooking at the evidence: The plaintiff submitted PX-2 and PX-3 as reports about the NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 and A1015/26. The defendant provided DX-1 with the raw NOTAM text from Notamify and DX-2 from Iran International. The raw NOTAM shows that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed except those operating sunrise-to-sunset with new CAA approval required for passenger flights. The Iran International report mentions denial of a nationwide notice but acknowledges the western region suspension with limited exceptions.\n\nThe key issue is whether this constitutes a broad regional closure with limited exceptions as per the rule. The rule's examples include the April 2024 western Iran closure as qualifying. The NOTAM text states closures except specific airports operating with permissions, which the rule explicitly says doesn't disqualify the closure because exceptions are permitted. The plaintiff argues it meets the broad-region pathway, while the defense claims it's a partial restriction.\n\nMy role is to decide based on preponderance of evidence. The raw NOTAM from DX-1 is the most specific evidence and does match the rule's description: a broad closure with limited exceptions (daylight-only operations under approval). The rule's wording says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure... will not disqualify such a closure.\" So even with some airports open under restrictions, this is still a qualified major closure.\n\nTherefore, the vote should be \"demonstrated\" because the evidence shows a broad closure in the western Tehran FIR region with permissible exceptions, meeting the rule's criteria. The rationale needs to be concise: mention the raw NOTAM confirming the closure with specific exceptions that fit under allowed limited exceptions.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"The raw NOTAM text confirms a broad closure of western Tehran FIR with specific exceptions operating under limited daylight hours and fresh approval requirements, which meets the rule's definition of a major closure with permissible limited exceptions."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":19120,"output":559,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19679,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782830095287,"responseId":"gen-1782830095-7BTab7rPHwrQU3N3EQ2g","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},"toolResults":[]}
{"type":"agent_end","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are council member C1 for AAR case arb-ex11a-20260630141638. Use the Pi MCP proxy tool named `mcp` to call AAR tools. The Pi proxy exposes AAR tools with `aar_` prefixes.\n\nEvery `mcp` call must have exactly this shape: a `tool` string and an `args` string. Do not include `action`, `server`, or `connect`. Do not pass `args` as an object.\n\nFirst call `mcp` with `{\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}`. If it returns `state: waiting`, call the same tool again with the returned `after_version`, using an args string such as `{\"after_version\":3}`. If it returns `state: ready`, read the returned prompt, turn, limits, remaining time, attempts remaining, and opportunity id.\n\nReview the visible arbitration record and admitted evidence. Use MCP tool calls for `aar_get_case`, `aar_list_evidence`, `aar_stat_evidence`, and `aar_read_evidence_range` when exact contents or provenance matter. You may use Pi's ordinary local tools to organize and analyze the record, but your vote must rely on admitted record evidence and the arbitration record.\n\nWhen ready, call `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote`, vote `demonstrated` or `not_demonstrated`, and a concise rationale grounded in the record. The `args` value must be a JSON string, for example `{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\"}`. The AAR prompt and tool list use unprefixed names such as `submit_council_vote`; in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`. Do not write tool-call markup as plain text. After `aar_submit_council_vote` returns `ok: true`, report that your vote was accepted and stop. Do not call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` again after your vote is accepted. If `aar_wait_for_opportunity` returns `state: done`, report that the case is done and stop. If it returns `state: failed` or `state: error`, report the returned message and stop. Do not ask the user for the next turn. Do not create a cron job. Do not listen for inbound HTTP.\n"}],"timestamp":1782830079554},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let's see. The user is council member C1 for the AAR case arb-ex11a-20260630141638. My job is to use the Pi MCP proxy tool to call AAR tools. The instructions say that every mcp call must have exactly two parameters: tool and args as a JSON string. No other parameters like action, server, or connect.\n\nFirst steps: call aar_wait_for_opportunity with empty args. Let's check the response.\n\nSo, the initial command should be mcp with tool \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args \"{}\".\n\nWait, the example given was: {\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}. Exactly that structure. So, I need to make sure that the args is a JSON string, so the string version of the JSON object.\n\nSo the first call is:\n\n{\n  \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n  \"args\": \"{}\"\n}\n\nAfter calling that, I need to check the response. If state is waiting, then use the returned after_version. If ready, read the prompt, turn, etc. Otherwise, handle other states.\n\nBut first, I need to execute that initial mcp call. Let's do that.\n\nWait, but when the user says \"First call mcp with {\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}\". So I need to generate that tool call right away.\n\nSo now, the assistant should output the tools call for that mcp function.\n\nThe tool call should be in XML tags with the JSON inside. Let me check the example in the tool descriptions. The mcp function has parameters: tool and args (string), and possibly others but the user says exactly this shape: tool and args string. So no other parameters.\n\nSo the arguments for mcp should be {\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}\n\nWait, the mcp function parameters have 'tool' and 'args' as properties. So the JSON for the mcp function's arguments would have 'tool' and 'args' keys. For example, when calling mcp, you pass tool and args as top-level properties in the mcp arguments.\n\nWait, the user says: \"Every mcp call must have exactly this shape: a tool string and an args string. Do not include action, server, or connect.\"\n\nSo for example, the args for the mcp function would be:\n\n{\n  \"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\n  \"args\": \"{}\"\n}\n\nBecause the mcp function's parameters are defined as having 'tool' and 'args' as possible properties. Looking back at the mcp tool definition:\n\nThe mcp function parameters have properties: action, args, connect, describe, regex, search, server, tool.\n\nBut the user's instruction says: \"Every mcp call must have exactly this shape: a tool string and an args string. Do not include action, server, or connect.\"\n\nSo for the first call, the mcp argument should be {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}\n\nYes. Because the mcp function's parameters allow 'tool' and 'args', which are required? Wait, looking at the mcp parameters:\n\nIn the mcp definition, the parameters are properties, but required are not listed. However, the user's instruction says: \"Each mcp call must have exactly this shape: a tool string and an args string. Do not include action, server, or connect.\"\n\nSo for this call, we set tool to \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and args as \"{}\", which is the JSON string of empty object.\n\nThus, the tool call should be:\n\n<tools>\n{\"name\": \"mcp\", \"arguments\": {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}}\n</tools>\n\nYes. So that's the first step.\n\nAfter this, I need to process the response and then proceed based on the response. But as per the user's instruction, I need to generate the next step based on the response. But since the user hasn't provided any response yet, I have to start by making the first call.\n\nSo the current step is to call mcp with tool \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\" and empty args.\n\nLet me confirm that the arguments for mcp are structured correctly. The mcp function's arguments must have tool and args, each being strings. Because args is supposed to be a JSON string. So in the mcp call's arguments, \"args\" key is a string containing the JSON.\n\nYes. So for example, if the args for the tool is an empty object, then args parameter is the string \"{}\".\n\nSo the tool call for mcp is {\"name\": \"mcp\", \"arguments\": {\"tool\": \"aar_wait_for_opportunity\", \"args\": \"{}\"}}\n\nYes. Let's make that call first.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_022d061fabea43788cf198","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":2406,"output":1043,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":3449,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782830079587,"responseId":"gen-1782830079-xuxQdZ1LajiOrKj9aPGp","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_022d061fabea43788cf198","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 13\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nmember_id: C1\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260630141638\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nremaining_ms: 885709\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"after_version\":13,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260630141638\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C1\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition is not about whether a prediction market, UMA, or any platform governance process reached the right result. It asks a factual question under the market rule: by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, did Iran initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace?\\n\\nThe current record contains one admitted case-packet item, ev_e61df84283cc_market-page. That packet proves the governing standard and the questions that will decide this case. A qualifying closure must be Iranian-initiated, not solely weather-related, and timely. It must also be major: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. The rule also draws two important lines. Limited cancellations, delays, or partial closures do not qualify. But limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure, such as flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not defeat qualification. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are not enough.\\n\\nThat admitted packet does not yet prove the occurrence facts. It does not itself establish that an Iranian aviation authority issued a specific May 22-May 25 closure, which airports were covered, whether commercial arrivals and departures were suspended, whether overflights were barred, or whether any exceptions were limited enough to preserve a broad closure. Those facts must be proved with source material, not assumption.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The case will likely turn on whether the late-May Iranian aviation restrictions, if proved by official NOTAM or equivalent authority material and corroborated reporting, were a broad security-driven closure of a major Iranian airspace region rather than a mere localized delay or third-party avoidance. If the evidence shows Iran shut the western Tehran FIR or the airports within that region to ordinary commercial operations, while allowing only daylight operations or flights with fresh official approval, then the exception language matters: controlled permission for limited flights may be consistent with a qualifying broad closure.\\n\\nThe strongest opposing theory is also clear from the rule. Defendant will likely argue that the relevant May 24 condition failed because the restriction was only partial: some airports allegedly remained operational, some flights could proceed with approval, and the platform outcome for the May 24 market is listed as No. Those points deserve scrutiny, but none ends the factual inquiry by itself. The record standard is preponderance of the evidence, and the rule asks what Iran actually initiated, not what traders later priced or how a platform displayed its result.\\n\\nThe decisive proof should therefore be the source chain: the official Iranian aviation notice or NOTAM; its effective time, expiry time, affected FIR sector and airports; its treatment of commercial arrivals, departures, and transit; and credible reporting that confirms how the notice operated in practice. Equally important will be any contrary source showing that listed airports continued ordinary commercial arrivals and departures without a broad suspension, or that the restrictions were imposed by third parties rather than Iran.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, plaintiff asks the council to keep the dispute focused on those rule elements. If the evidence shows a broad, non-weather, Iranian-initiated regional closure by the deadline, limited official exceptions should not be allowed to turn a qualifying closure into a non-event. If the evidence instead shows only scattered delays or narrow localized restrictions, plaintiff will not have met the burden. The forthcoming record should decide that factual line.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff bears the burden to prove the rule’s factual condition, not merely to point to tension in the region, airline caution, or market chatter. The current admitted record is narrow. The only evidence item is ev_e61df84283cc_market-page, a case-packet text file with the market metadata, rule text, examples, and arbitration notes. It establishes the legal test. It does not establish that Iran actually initiated a qualifying closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThat distinction matters. The rule does not resolve “Yes” for any aviation disruption in Iran. It requires a major, Iranian-initiated, non-weather closure. The case packet defines a major closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, generally applying across Iran or such a region. It separately provides that a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports would qualify. But the same packet draws a limiting line: limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are also insufficient.\\n\\nDefendant’s opening theory is therefore straightforward: this case should turn on exact scope, not labels. Plaintiff must produce the official Iranian aviation source, or a reliably captured equivalent source chain, showing what was closed, when it became effective, when it expired, which airspace or airports were covered, and whether commercial transit, arrivals, and departures were actually suspended broadly enough to meet the rule. A reference to “western airspace,” “airport restrictions,” or “approval required” is not self-proving. It could describe a broad qualifying regional closure; it could also describe a partial, conditional, or airport-specific restriction that the rule expressly excludes.\\n\\nThe packet itself identifies the right source classes: official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. At this stage, none of that occurrence evidence is admitted. The record does not yet contain the NOTAM text, a Civil Aviation Organization notice, airport operational data, flight status records, or a complete chain showing that any reported restriction was official, timely, non-weather, and major within the rule’s terms.\\n\\nSeveral factual questions will decide the case. First, did Iran itself initiate the restriction, as opposed to airlines, foreign regulators, or risk advisories reacting to conflict? Second, did the restriction bar ordinary commercial overflight, arrivals, and departures across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region, or did it leave substantial commercial operations available by daylight, route, airport, or per-flight approval? Third, if plaintiff uses the listed-airport pathway, were commercial arrivals and departures completely suspended at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN? Fourth, were any exceptions genuinely limited exceptions to a broad closure, or were they broad operating permissions that make the event partial rather than major?\\n\\nDefendant does not ask the council to decide now that no closure happened. The defendant asks the council to hold plaintiff to the rule. If later admitted evidence contains an official, authenticated notice proving a broad regional shutdown with only narrow exceptions, plaintiff may have a serious argument under the broad-region language. But if the evidence shows only partial airport closures, daylight operations, approval-based continued service, airline avoidance, or ambiguous secondary reporting without the official source text, the proposition should fail.\\n\\nThe current record proves the standard and the burden. It does not prove the event. Until plaintiff supplies the source chain and operational facts, the preponderance remains against finding that the May 24 market condition was satisfied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the preponderance now favors the proposition.\\n\\nPX-1 supplies the rule. It asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited partial closures do not qualify, but limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the occurrence facts. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region, OIIX. It identifies the official act as Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, issued Friday, May 22, effective immediately and valid until May 25, ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR. PX-2 further reports that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were restricted to daylight hours with fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same core facts: NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran FIR, only a limited number of facilities could operate in daylight, and airlines needed fresh Iranian CAA approval before passenger flights in affected areas.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy each element. First, initiation: both reports attribute the restriction to Iran's aviation authority through a specific NOTAM, not to airlines, foreign regulators, or market commentary. Second, timing: the reported NOTAM began May 22 and remained valid until May 25, so it was in force before the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather cause: the reports place the measure in a security and military-diplomatic context, not weather. Fourth, magnitude: western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reported measure was not a scattered airport delay. It suspended civil flight permits in the western OIIX sector and shut all airports in the western part of that FIR.\\n\\nDefendant's best point is that some airports remained operational under daylight and fresh-approval limits. But that is not fatal under PX-1. The rule expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify the closure. A system in which ordinary civil flight permits in the western sector are suspended, airports in the western FIR are shut, and the remaining national operations require daylight timing and fresh official approval is not normal commercial availability. It is a broad Iranian-controlled suspension with limited permissions.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to prove the separate listed-airport pathway if the broad-major-region pathway is met. And that matters because PX-2 says several listed airports were among the eight still operating under restrictions. The better reading is therefore not that every listed airport was completely shut; it is that Iran closed a major airspace region and permitted only constrained exceptions elsewhere. That is exactly the distinction PX-1 preserves.\\n\\nThe proof is not perfect. The official NOTAM text itself is not in the record, and PX-2 appears to report the NOTAM detail through Gulf News. That limits weight. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where two admitted reports identify the same official notice number, same authority, same dates, same FIR, same closure of western-region airports, and same approval/daylight restrictions. No admitted contrary source shows the NOTAM was fake, weather-based, third-party-imposed, or merely a few isolated cancellations.\\n\\nOn this record, the more likely factual conclusion is that by May 24, Iran had initiated a non-weather broad closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the full argument record still does not prove the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1 is the controlling rule. It requires more than a disruption: Iran must initiate a non-weather “major closure” by the deadline. A major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also has a separate listed-airport path: complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two named airports. It expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary reports, not the official NOTAM. They help identify a lead, but their own contents show why the lead is not enough. PX-2 says eight airports remained operational, including several listed in PX-1, and that those airports could operate in daylight with fresh per-flight CAA approval. PX-3 likewise describes closure of “airports” across the western section of the Tehran FIR, with a limited number of facilities permitted to operate during daylight and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights in affected areas. That is not proof of a complete suspension at two listed airports; it is the opposite.\\n\\nDX-1, the Notamify capture of the raw NOTAM text, is the most specific evidence now in the record. It narrows, rather than expands, plaintiff’s case. A1010/26 is categorized as AD Airport Operations and says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except specified airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. It does not say the Tehran FIR is closed to overflights. It does not identify ATS-route closures. It does not say commercial flights transiting Iranian airspace are suspended. It is an airport-operations NOTAM with named operating exceptions.\\n\\nDX-1 also shows that before the deadline A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 and expanded the exceptions. The replacement listed OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR, and OIAM as operational from sunrise to sunset, again with permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. OISS is Shiraz and OIFM is Isfahan; PX-2 also lists IKA, Mehrabad, Mashhad, Shiraz, and Isfahan among airports that remained operational in some form. On the listed-airport pathway, plaintiff has not shown complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two named airports.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proved the broad-region pathway. The rule’s phrase is not merely “some airports in a region were restricted.” It requires broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The admitted raw text speaks in terms of airports in the west part of the FIR, and then carves out numerous operating airports. It permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. Plaintiff asks the council to treat that as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions, but the record equally, and more precisely, supports a partial airport restriction with substantial conditional operations.\\n\\nDX-2 adds a provenance and conflict problem. Iran International reported that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization denied a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule, while also acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is not a clean defense win, because it confirms some airport restrictions. But it defeats plaintiff’s attempt to turn two article summaries into a settled official source chain proving a countrywide or major-region airspace closure.\\n\\nThe source chain remains weak. No official Iranian CAA page, ICAO bulletin, original NOTAM feed record, airport movement record, or flight-data exhibit is admitted. PX-2 even attributes the key official-NOTAM claim to Gulf News rather than reproducing the underlying source. DX-1 is an aggregator capture, useful for text, but even that text supports conditional airport operations and does not prove overflight or route closure.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s best point is the rule’s “limited exceptions” clause. But exceptions are limited only against an otherwise broad closure. The council cannot assume the predicate. Here the admitted evidence shows named airports operational, permissions available for civil IFR passenger flights, an expanded exception list before the deadline, and no admitted proof that commercial transit through a major airspace region was broadly suspended.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition is not more likely true than false. The council should find that plaintiff proved a partial, conditional western-airport restriction, not a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s case; it supplies the specificity defendant said was missing.\\n\\nDX-1 is now the most exact source in the record. Its raw A1010/26 text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating from sunrise to sunset; all previous permissions are suspended for all operators; new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. A1015/26 replaces A1010/26 and repeats the same structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except a listed set, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat is not ordinary commercial operation. It is a general closure in a defined major Iranian aviation region, with named exceptions and an official permission regime. PX-1 expressly anticipates this situation: limited exceptions to a broad closure, including flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not disqualify a closure.\\n\\nDefendant tries to make overflight-route closure the decisive test because DX-1 is categorized as airport operations and does not list ATS-route closures. But PX-1 does not require every route, altitude, or overflight track to be separately closed. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The west part of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in that west part, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that region, especially as to arrivals and departures.\\n\\nDefendant is right that plaintiff should not lean on the separate listed-airport complete-suspension pathway. The stronger and sufficient pathway is the broad-major-region clause. The presence of exceptions, and even A1015’s expanded exception list, does not convert the measure into a few scattered delays. The operative rule distinguishes partial closures from broad closures with limited exceptions. DX-1’s phrase “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” is the language of a broad closure with exceptions.\\n\\nDX-2 is also narrower than defendant suggests. It denies a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and refers to a social-media notice. But the proposition does not require countrywide restrictions. More importantly, DX-2 acknowledges that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization had said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That confirms the core event; it only disputes an overbroad nationwide version.\\n\\nThe final factual line is therefore clear. If the rule required total nationwide shutdown or complete closure of two listed airports, defendant would have a stronger case. It does not. It allows a major-region closure and preserves limited official exceptions. On the admitted raw NOTAM text, Iran initiated a non-weather closure of the west part of the Tehran FIR by the deadline, suspended prior permissions for all operators, and allowed only constrained CAA-approved passenger operations. That meets the rule by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the sharpest issue: whether DX-1 shows a broad major-region closure with limited exceptions, or a partial airport-operations restriction. The record supports the latter.\\n\\nDefendant does not deny that DX-1 shows a real Iranian aviation restriction, in force before the deadline, in a non-weather context. The problem is scope. PX-1 does not count every Iranian aviation restriction. It requires a major closure: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It then separately counts complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Limited or partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nDX-1’s raw text is precise. It is coded QFALC and presented as AD Airport Operations. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except named airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset. It then says previous permissions are suspended and new permission must be requested for operation of civil IFR passenger flights. That is evidence about airport operations and permissioning. It is not evidence that the Tehran FIR, or the western part of it, was closed to commercial transit. It does not identify closed airways, closed overflight routes, an FIR-wide airspace closure, altitude restrictions, or a suspension of all commercial flights transiting the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule does not require every route or altitude to be listed. Fair enough. But plaintiff still must prove the thing the rule does require: a broad closure or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. The only raw text in evidence speaks in narrower airport terms and simultaneously permits civil IFR passenger operations at named airports with CAA permission.\\n\\nThe “limited exceptions” clause does not solve that gap. It protects a closure already shown to be broad; it does not transform a partial restriction into a broad closure. Here the exceptions are not incidental: A1010/26 listed eight operating airports, and A1015/26 expanded that list to twelve before the deadline. The record also shows listed market airports remained operational in some form. That defeats the separate complete-suspension pathway and reinforces the partial nature of the measure.\\n\\nDX-2 matters for the same reason. Plaintiff is right that it acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. But it also reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule. That conflict is not proof of “No” by itself; it is a warning against overreading an airport-activity suspension as a major airspace closure.\\n\\nAfter rebuttal, the decisive gap remains unchanged. The record proves restricted, permission-based airport operations in western Iran. It does not prove a broad suspension of commercial transit, arrivals, and departures through a major Iranian airspace region, and it does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports. Under the market rule’s own exclusion of partial closures, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you the precise source defendant said was missing: the raw NOTAM text. The proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The plaintiff does not have to prove total nationwide closure or complete suspension at two listed airports if the broad-region pathway is satisfied. PX-1 defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region, and it expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record evidence is the NOTAM text in DX-1, read with the corroborating reports in PX-2 and PX-3. A1010/26, effective May 22 and valid past the May 24 deadline, states that all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset. It also states that all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for civil IFR passenger flights. A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 before the deadline, expanded the exception list, but kept the same core command: all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports, prior permissions are suspended for all operators, and new Iran CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat is an Iranian-initiated, non-weather aviation restriction in force before the deadline. The non-weather context is supported by PX-2, PX-3, and even the framing of DX-2; no record evidence suggests weather. The restriction was imposed through Iran CAA/CAO channels. It applied to the west part of the Tehran FIR, a major Iranian aviation region. It closed all airports in that region except named ones and converted ordinary civil IFR passenger operations into daylight, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is that DX-1 is coded as airport operations and does not separately list closed overflight routes, airways, or altitudes. But PX-1 does not require a total FIR route closure. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in the region. Commercial flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except specified daylight airports, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and every civil IFR passenger flight needs fresh CAA approval, commercial arrivals and departures in that major region are broadly suspended.\\n\\nDefendant’s other point is that the exceptions are too numerous. That would matter if the rule treated every exception as fatal. It does not. The question is whether the record shows a broad closure with limited exceptions or merely scattered delays. The text “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” answers that question. It is a general closure first, with exceptions second. The fresh-permission requirement confirms that the exceptions were controlled permissions, not normal operations.\\n\\nDX-2 does not change the result. It denies a new nationwide or social-media notice and says flights were generally operating according to plan. But it also acknowledges the earlier Friday statement that activity at airports in the western Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only limited airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That is not a denial of plaintiff’s actual theory. Plaintiff’s theory is not nationwide closure; it is major-region closure.\\n\\nThe record is imperfect in provenance because the official Iranian source page is not before you, and Notamify is an aggregator. But the preponderance standard asks what is more likely. The raw NOTAM text, two corroborating reports, and even defendant’s contrary article all converge on the same core fact: by May 24, Iran had suspended ordinary airport activity in the west part of the Tehran FIR and allowed only constrained, permission-based civil passenger operations at named airports.\\n\\nUnder PX-1, that is a major non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the question is not whether Iran imposed a real aviation restriction. It did. The question is whether plaintiff proved a major closure within PX-1’s specific market rule. On this record, that burden is not met.\\n\\nPX-1 is demanding in two ways. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Alternatively, it requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. And it expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\\n\\nThe listed-airport pathway is gone. PX-2 itself says several listed airports remained operational under restrictions. DX-1’s replacement NOTAM A1015/26 includes additional operating exceptions, including OISS and OIFM. Whether those operations were daylight-only and permission-based, they were not a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports.\\n\\nThat leaves only the broad-region pathway. Plaintiff’s best evidence is DX-1, the raw Notamify text. Defendant agrees it carries the most weight. But read it carefully. A1010/26 and A1015/26 are airport-operations notices. They say airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports operating sunrise-to-sunset; prior permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights. They do not say the western Tehran FIR is closed. They do not close overflight routes. They do not identify airways, altitude blocks, or an FIR-wide suspension. They do not prove that commercial flights transiting the region were broadly suspended.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to bridge that gap by inference: airport closures plus permission requirements should be treated as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions. But the competing inference is at least as strong: this was a partial, conditional airport restriction, with numerous operating airports and an approval path for civil IFR passenger service. PX-1’s limited-exception clause cannot erase PX-1’s partial-closure exclusion. A closure is not “broad” merely because it starts with the words “all airports” when the same operative text lists many operating exceptions and permits passenger flights with approval.\\n\\nDX-2 reinforces caution. It reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is consistent with a limited airport-activity suspension. It is not proof of a major airspace closure.\\n\\nThe evidentiary gaps also matter. There is no official Iranian CAA or ICAO artifact in the record, no airport movement data, no flight-tracking exhibit showing actual suspension, and no route or overflight closure record. PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary summaries; DX-1 is an aggregator capture. The council can credit them for the airport restriction they show, but should not inflate them into proof of facts they do not contain.\\n\\nPreponderance means more likely than not. The record makes it more likely that Iran imposed a significant, non-weather, permission-based restriction on western Iranian airport operations. It does not make it more likely that Iran initiated a major closure of its airspace or a major airspace region as PX-1 defines that term. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1: Market rule and arbitration proposition\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2: Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: The Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- The subheadline states that only eight Iranian airports remained operational under daylight-only restrictions.\\n- The article reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX).\\n- It reports that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, citing Gulf News.\\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational: Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas.\\n- It states that even at those airports, flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- It reports flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor.\\n- The article characterizes the NOTAM as formalizing the most extensive restrictions in weeks amid non-weather military/diplomatic tensions.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3: Siasat corroborating report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Siasat.com, \\\"Iran closes western airspace amid reports of possible US military action\\\". By Sakina Fatima. Published May 23, 2026 8:33 am IST; updated May 23, 2026 9:44 am IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- The article reports that Iran imposed new airspace restrictions on Saturday, May 23, amid reports that the Trump administration was reviewing military options against Tehran.\\n- It identifies a Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, and reports that it announced the closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran Flight Information Region.\\n- It reports that only a limited number of facilities were permitted to operate during daylight hours.\\n- It states the restrictions were expected to remain in place until Monday, May 25, with airlines required to seek fresh approval from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority before operating passenger flights in affected areas.\\n- The article places the announcement amid heightened regional tensions and diplomatic activity, including U.S. contingency planning and Iran-related negotiations; it does not describe weather as the cause.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-Rule: market rule and proposition\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1: Notamify raw NOTAM text for A1010/26 and A1015/26\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2: Iran International report on official denial and exempted airport activity\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1: Raw NOTAM text confirms western Tehran FIR airport closures\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2: Iran International confirms prior western-FIR airport suspension despite denying a new nationwide notice\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1: raw NOTAM text shows airport-operations restriction and operating exceptions\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2: official-denial report shows ambiguity and limited airport-suspension framing\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace closure, May 23 2026 (ev_6877e32e36e2_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-6877e32e36e2)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `6877e32e36e2b58bf10a9b2d917614c815931dc94d707627c69bb1fc195f509c`\\nBytes: 1524\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, valid until May 25, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and limiting remaining airports to daylight operations with fresh per-flight CAA approval.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Siasat report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, May 23 2026 (ev_25136676d648_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-25136676d648)\\nSource: https://www.siasat.com/trump-considers-new-iran-strikes-as-diplomacy-enters-critical-phase-3475705/\\nSHA-256: `25136676d648360a3c4d2329f64e071677d51e8d2dc36aa30b7dbcf314121c79`\\nBytes: 1103\\nRelevance: Corroborates that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western Tehran FIR, with limited daylight operations and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights; describes non-weather military/diplomatic context.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw text for OIIX A1010/26 and replacement A1015/26 (ev_5e5109b5ca63_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-5e5109b5ca63)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 and https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nSHA-256: `5e5109b5ca632110b53c1e6f333fa92259a70d8b970b57de188d7b8dbcc1bce7`\\nBytes: 2376\\nRelevance: Shows the raw NOTAM wording available from a NOTAM aggregator. The text frames the measure as airport-operations closures in the west part of Tehran FIR, lists exceptions operating sunrise-to-sunset, requires new permission for civil IFR passenger flights, and shows A1015/26 replacing A1010/26 with a longer exception list before the deadline.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country (ev_6057a17cc5bf_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-6057a17cc5bf)\\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\\nSHA-256: `6057a17cc5bf9d03bc6a13a3f87c381c3974e116d8d6e2a3a9ecd39961ab6e61`\\nBytes: 1142\\nRelevance: Provides a contrary/source-chain complication: Iran's Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson reportedly denied a new official aviation notice imposing nationwide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while the same report acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nPlaintiff searched for the decisive source class: official Iranian aviation notice/NOTAM, source-specific public reports, and adverse material. The official NOTAM artifact was not obtained in this opportunity. The submitted reports identify the same NOTAM number, OIIX A1010/26, the same May 22-May 25 period, the same western Tehran FIR region, and the same daylight/per-flight approval restrictions. This is secondary-source proof, with a provenance limitation: PX-2 says the NOTAM detail was reported by Gulf News, and PX-3 independently reports the NOTAM but does not attach the official notice. Adverse check: defendant's partial-operation theory is supported by the reported continued operation of eight airports under daylight and fresh approval; plaintiff treats that as a limited-exception issue, not as proof of ordinary commercial availability.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-chain and scope ledger\\nInspected all visible evidence with list/stat/read. Plaintiff evidence consists of secondary report captures; neither is the official NOTAM. Targeted searches for A1010/26 and contrary official-denial language found Notamify raw NOTAM pages and an Iran International report, both submitted as defendant evidence. The decisive unresolved gaps are the absence of an official CAA/ICAO source artifact, no admitted overflight or route-closure record, no airport movement data, and no proof of complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence read\\nPlaintiff read defendant's two new evidence items. The Notamify item states that all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except named sunrise-to-sunset airports, that all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and that new permission from CAA/Iran CAA was required for civil IFR passenger flights. The Iran International item denies a new nationwide/social-media notice but also acknowledges the earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with limited sunrise-to-sunset exemptions.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885709,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":9},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":13,\"version\":13}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 13\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nmember_id: C1\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260630141638\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nremaining_ms: 885709\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"after_version\":13,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260630141638\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C1\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition is not about whether a prediction market, UMA, or any platform governance process reached the right result. It asks a factual question under the market rule: by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, did Iran initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace?\\n\\nThe current record contains one admitted case-packet item, ev_e61df84283cc_market-page. That packet proves the governing standard and the questions that will decide this case. A qualifying closure must be Iranian-initiated, not solely weather-related, and timely. It must also be major: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. The rule also draws two important lines. Limited cancellations, delays, or partial closures do not qualify. But limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure, such as flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not defeat qualification. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are not enough.\\n\\nThat admitted packet does not yet prove the occurrence facts. It does not itself establish that an Iranian aviation authority issued a specific May 22-May 25 closure, which airports were covered, whether commercial arrivals and departures were suspended, whether overflights were barred, or whether any exceptions were limited enough to preserve a broad closure. Those facts must be proved with source material, not assumption.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The case will likely turn on whether the late-May Iranian aviation restrictions, if proved by official NOTAM or equivalent authority material and corroborated reporting, were a broad security-driven closure of a major Iranian airspace region rather than a mere localized delay or third-party avoidance. If the evidence shows Iran shut the western Tehran FIR or the airports within that region to ordinary commercial operations, while allowing only daylight operations or flights with fresh official approval, then the exception language matters: controlled permission for limited flights may be consistent with a qualifying broad closure.\\n\\nThe strongest opposing theory is also clear from the rule. Defendant will likely argue that the relevant May 24 condition failed because the restriction was only partial: some airports allegedly remained operational, some flights could proceed with approval, and the platform outcome for the May 24 market is listed as No. Those points deserve scrutiny, but none ends the factual inquiry by itself. The record standard is preponderance of the evidence, and the rule asks what Iran actually initiated, not what traders later priced or how a platform displayed its result.\\n\\nThe decisive proof should therefore be the source chain: the official Iranian aviation notice or NOTAM; its effective time, expiry time, affected FIR sector and airports; its treatment of commercial arrivals, departures, and transit; and credible reporting that confirms how the notice operated in practice. Equally important will be any contrary source showing that listed airports continued ordinary commercial arrivals and departures without a broad suspension, or that the restrictions were imposed by third parties rather than Iran.\\n\\nAt this opening stage, plaintiff asks the council to keep the dispute focused on those rule elements. If the evidence shows a broad, non-weather, Iranian-initiated regional closure by the deadline, limited official exceptions should not be allowed to turn a qualifying closure into a non-event. If the evidence instead shows only scattered delays or narrow localized restrictions, plaintiff will not have met the burden. The forthcoming record should decide that factual line.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff bears the burden to prove the rule’s factual condition, not merely to point to tension in the region, airline caution, or market chatter. The current admitted record is narrow. The only evidence item is ev_e61df84283cc_market-page, a case-packet text file with the market metadata, rule text, examples, and arbitration notes. It establishes the legal test. It does not establish that Iran actually initiated a qualifying closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nThat distinction matters. The rule does not resolve “Yes” for any aviation disruption in Iran. It requires a major, Iranian-initiated, non-weather closure. The case packet defines a major closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, generally applying across Iran or such a region. It separately provides that a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports would qualify. But the same packet draws a limiting line: limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are also insufficient.\\n\\nDefendant’s opening theory is therefore straightforward: this case should turn on exact scope, not labels. Plaintiff must produce the official Iranian aviation source, or a reliably captured equivalent source chain, showing what was closed, when it became effective, when it expired, which airspace or airports were covered, and whether commercial transit, arrivals, and departures were actually suspended broadly enough to meet the rule. A reference to “western airspace,” “airport restrictions,” or “approval required” is not self-proving. It could describe a broad qualifying regional closure; it could also describe a partial, conditional, or airport-specific restriction that the rule expressly excludes.\\n\\nThe packet itself identifies the right source classes: official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. At this stage, none of that occurrence evidence is admitted. The record does not yet contain the NOTAM text, a Civil Aviation Organization notice, airport operational data, flight status records, or a complete chain showing that any reported restriction was official, timely, non-weather, and major within the rule’s terms.\\n\\nSeveral factual questions will decide the case. First, did Iran itself initiate the restriction, as opposed to airlines, foreign regulators, or risk advisories reacting to conflict? Second, did the restriction bar ordinary commercial overflight, arrivals, and departures across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region, or did it leave substantial commercial operations available by daylight, route, airport, or per-flight approval? Third, if plaintiff uses the listed-airport pathway, were commercial arrivals and departures completely suspended at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN? Fourth, were any exceptions genuinely limited exceptions to a broad closure, or were they broad operating permissions that make the event partial rather than major?\\n\\nDefendant does not ask the council to decide now that no closure happened. The defendant asks the council to hold plaintiff to the rule. If later admitted evidence contains an official, authenticated notice proving a broad regional shutdown with only narrow exceptions, plaintiff may have a serious argument under the broad-region language. But if the evidence shows only partial airport closures, daylight operations, approval-based continued service, airline avoidance, or ambiguous secondary reporting without the official source text, the proposition should fail.\\n\\nThe current record proves the standard and the burden. It does not prove the event. Until plaintiff supplies the source chain and operational facts, the preponderance remains against finding that the May 24 market condition was satisfied.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the preponderance now favors the proposition.\\n\\nPX-1 supplies the rule. It asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited partial closures do not qualify, but limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the occurrence facts. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region, OIIX. It identifies the official act as Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, issued Friday, May 22, effective immediately and valid until May 25, ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR. PX-2 further reports that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were restricted to daylight hours with fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same core facts: NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran FIR, only a limited number of facilities could operate in daylight, and airlines needed fresh Iranian CAA approval before passenger flights in affected areas.\\n\\nThose facts satisfy each element. First, initiation: both reports attribute the restriction to Iran's aviation authority through a specific NOTAM, not to airlines, foreign regulators, or market commentary. Second, timing: the reported NOTAM began May 22 and remained valid until May 25, so it was in force before the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather cause: the reports place the measure in a security and military-diplomatic context, not weather. Fourth, magnitude: western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reported measure was not a scattered airport delay. It suspended civil flight permits in the western OIIX sector and shut all airports in the western part of that FIR.\\n\\nDefendant's best point is that some airports remained operational under daylight and fresh-approval limits. But that is not fatal under PX-1. The rule expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify the closure. A system in which ordinary civil flight permits in the western sector are suspended, airports in the western FIR are shut, and the remaining national operations require daylight timing and fresh official approval is not normal commercial availability. It is a broad Iranian-controlled suspension with limited permissions.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to prove the separate listed-airport pathway if the broad-major-region pathway is met. And that matters because PX-2 says several listed airports were among the eight still operating under restrictions. The better reading is therefore not that every listed airport was completely shut; it is that Iran closed a major airspace region and permitted only constrained exceptions elsewhere. That is exactly the distinction PX-1 preserves.\\n\\nThe proof is not perfect. The official NOTAM text itself is not in the record, and PX-2 appears to report the NOTAM detail through Gulf News. That limits weight. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where two admitted reports identify the same official notice number, same authority, same dates, same FIR, same closure of western-region airports, and same approval/daylight restrictions. No admitted contrary source shows the NOTAM was fake, weather-based, third-party-imposed, or merely a few isolated cancellations.\\n\\nOn this record, the more likely factual conclusion is that by May 24, Iran had initiated a non-weather broad closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the full argument record still does not prove the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1 is the controlling rule. It requires more than a disruption: Iran must initiate a non-weather “major closure” by the deadline. A major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also has a separate listed-airport path: complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two named airports. It expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary reports, not the official NOTAM. They help identify a lead, but their own contents show why the lead is not enough. PX-2 says eight airports remained operational, including several listed in PX-1, and that those airports could operate in daylight with fresh per-flight CAA approval. PX-3 likewise describes closure of “airports” across the western section of the Tehran FIR, with a limited number of facilities permitted to operate during daylight and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights in affected areas. That is not proof of a complete suspension at two listed airports; it is the opposite.\\n\\nDX-1, the Notamify capture of the raw NOTAM text, is the most specific evidence now in the record. It narrows, rather than expands, plaintiff’s case. A1010/26 is categorized as AD Airport Operations and says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except specified airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. It does not say the Tehran FIR is closed to overflights. It does not identify ATS-route closures. It does not say commercial flights transiting Iranian airspace are suspended. It is an airport-operations NOTAM with named operating exceptions.\\n\\nDX-1 also shows that before the deadline A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 and expanded the exceptions. The replacement listed OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR, and OIAM as operational from sunrise to sunset, again with permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. OISS is Shiraz and OIFM is Isfahan; PX-2 also lists IKA, Mehrabad, Mashhad, Shiraz, and Isfahan among airports that remained operational in some form. On the listed-airport pathway, plaintiff has not shown complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two named airports.\\n\\nNor has plaintiff proved the broad-region pathway. The rule’s phrase is not merely “some airports in a region were restricted.” It requires broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The admitted raw text speaks in terms of airports in the west part of the FIR, and then carves out numerous operating airports. It permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. Plaintiff asks the council to treat that as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions, but the record equally, and more precisely, supports a partial airport restriction with substantial conditional operations.\\n\\nDX-2 adds a provenance and conflict problem. Iran International reported that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization denied a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule, while also acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is not a clean defense win, because it confirms some airport restrictions. But it defeats plaintiff’s attempt to turn two article summaries into a settled official source chain proving a countrywide or major-region airspace closure.\\n\\nThe source chain remains weak. No official Iranian CAA page, ICAO bulletin, original NOTAM feed record, airport movement record, or flight-data exhibit is admitted. PX-2 even attributes the key official-NOTAM claim to Gulf News rather than reproducing the underlying source. DX-1 is an aggregator capture, useful for text, but even that text supports conditional airport operations and does not prove overflight or route closure.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s best point is the rule’s “limited exceptions” clause. But exceptions are limited only against an otherwise broad closure. The council cannot assume the predicate. Here the admitted evidence shows named airports operational, permissions available for civil IFR passenger flights, an expanded exception list before the deadline, and no admitted proof that commercial transit through a major airspace region was broadly suspended.\\n\\nOn this record, the proposition is not more likely true than false. The council should find that plaintiff proved a partial, conditional western-airport restriction, not a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s case; it supplies the specificity defendant said was missing.\\n\\nDX-1 is now the most exact source in the record. Its raw A1010/26 text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating from sunrise to sunset; all previous permissions are suspended for all operators; new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. A1015/26 replaces A1010/26 and repeats the same structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except a listed set, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat is not ordinary commercial operation. It is a general closure in a defined major Iranian aviation region, with named exceptions and an official permission regime. PX-1 expressly anticipates this situation: limited exceptions to a broad closure, including flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not disqualify a closure.\\n\\nDefendant tries to make overflight-route closure the decisive test because DX-1 is categorized as airport operations and does not list ATS-route closures. But PX-1 does not require every route, altitude, or overflight track to be separately closed. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The west part of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in that west part, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that region, especially as to arrivals and departures.\\n\\nDefendant is right that plaintiff should not lean on the separate listed-airport complete-suspension pathway. The stronger and sufficient pathway is the broad-major-region clause. The presence of exceptions, and even A1015’s expanded exception list, does not convert the measure into a few scattered delays. The operative rule distinguishes partial closures from broad closures with limited exceptions. DX-1’s phrase “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” is the language of a broad closure with exceptions.\\n\\nDX-2 is also narrower than defendant suggests. It denies a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and refers to a social-media notice. But the proposition does not require countrywide restrictions. More importantly, DX-2 acknowledges that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization had said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That confirms the core event; it only disputes an overbroad nationwide version.\\n\\nThe final factual line is therefore clear. If the rule required total nationwide shutdown or complete closure of two listed airports, defendant would have a stronger case. It does not. It allows a major-region closure and preserves limited official exceptions. On the admitted raw NOTAM text, Iran initiated a non-weather closure of the west part of the Tehran FIR by the deadline, suspended prior permissions for all operators, and allowed only constrained CAA-approved passenger operations. That meets the rule by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the sharpest issue: whether DX-1 shows a broad major-region closure with limited exceptions, or a partial airport-operations restriction. The record supports the latter.\\n\\nDefendant does not deny that DX-1 shows a real Iranian aviation restriction, in force before the deadline, in a non-weather context. The problem is scope. PX-1 does not count every Iranian aviation restriction. It requires a major closure: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It then separately counts complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Limited or partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nDX-1’s raw text is precise. It is coded QFALC and presented as AD Airport Operations. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except named airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset. It then says previous permissions are suspended and new permission must be requested for operation of civil IFR passenger flights. That is evidence about airport operations and permissioning. It is not evidence that the Tehran FIR, or the western part of it, was closed to commercial transit. It does not identify closed airways, closed overflight routes, an FIR-wide airspace closure, altitude restrictions, or a suspension of all commercial flights transiting the region.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the rule does not require every route or altitude to be listed. Fair enough. But plaintiff still must prove the thing the rule does require: a broad closure or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. The only raw text in evidence speaks in narrower airport terms and simultaneously permits civil IFR passenger operations at named airports with CAA permission.\\n\\nThe “limited exceptions” clause does not solve that gap. It protects a closure already shown to be broad; it does not transform a partial restriction into a broad closure. Here the exceptions are not incidental: A1010/26 listed eight operating airports, and A1015/26 expanded that list to twelve before the deadline. The record also shows listed market airports remained operational in some form. That defeats the separate complete-suspension pathway and reinforces the partial nature of the measure.\\n\\nDX-2 matters for the same reason. Plaintiff is right that it acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. But it also reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule. That conflict is not proof of “No” by itself; it is a warning against overreading an airport-activity suspension as a major airspace closure.\\n\\nAfter rebuttal, the decisive gap remains unchanged. The record proves restricted, permission-based airport operations in western Iran. It does not prove a broad suspension of commercial transit, arrivals, and departures through a major Iranian airspace region, and it does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports. Under the market rule’s own exclusion of partial closures, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you the precise source defendant said was missing: the raw NOTAM text. The proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The plaintiff does not have to prove total nationwide closure or complete suspension at two listed airports if the broad-region pathway is satisfied. PX-1 defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region, and it expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe decisive record evidence is the NOTAM text in DX-1, read with the corroborating reports in PX-2 and PX-3. A1010/26, effective May 22 and valid past the May 24 deadline, states that all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset. It also states that all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for civil IFR passenger flights. A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 before the deadline, expanded the exception list, but kept the same core command: all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports, prior permissions are suspended for all operators, and new Iran CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n\\nThat is an Iranian-initiated, non-weather aviation restriction in force before the deadline. The non-weather context is supported by PX-2, PX-3, and even the framing of DX-2; no record evidence suggests weather. The restriction was imposed through Iran CAA/CAO channels. It applied to the west part of the Tehran FIR, a major Iranian aviation region. It closed all airports in that region except named ones and converted ordinary civil IFR passenger operations into daylight, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nDefendant’s best point is that DX-1 is coded as airport operations and does not separately list closed overflight routes, airways, or altitudes. But PX-1 does not require a total FIR route closure. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in the region. Commercial flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except specified daylight airports, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and every civil IFR passenger flight needs fresh CAA approval, commercial arrivals and departures in that major region are broadly suspended.\\n\\nDefendant’s other point is that the exceptions are too numerous. That would matter if the rule treated every exception as fatal. It does not. The question is whether the record shows a broad closure with limited exceptions or merely scattered delays. The text “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” answers that question. It is a general closure first, with exceptions second. The fresh-permission requirement confirms that the exceptions were controlled permissions, not normal operations.\\n\\nDX-2 does not change the result. It denies a new nationwide or social-media notice and says flights were generally operating according to plan. But it also acknowledges the earlier Friday statement that activity at airports in the western Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only limited airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That is not a denial of plaintiff’s actual theory. Plaintiff’s theory is not nationwide closure; it is major-region closure.\\n\\nThe record is imperfect in provenance because the official Iranian source page is not before you, and Notamify is an aggregator. But the preponderance standard asks what is more likely. The raw NOTAM text, two corroborating reports, and even defendant’s contrary article all converge on the same core fact: by May 24, Iran had suspended ordinary airport activity in the west part of the Tehran FIR and allowed only constrained, permission-based civil passenger operations at named airports.\\n\\nUnder PX-1, that is a major non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the question is not whether Iran imposed a real aviation restriction. It did. The question is whether plaintiff proved a major closure within PX-1’s specific market rule. On this record, that burden is not met.\\n\\nPX-1 is demanding in two ways. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Alternatively, it requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. And it expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\\n\\nThe listed-airport pathway is gone. PX-2 itself says several listed airports remained operational under restrictions. DX-1’s replacement NOTAM A1015/26 includes additional operating exceptions, including OISS and OIFM. Whether those operations were daylight-only and permission-based, they were not a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports.\\n\\nThat leaves only the broad-region pathway. Plaintiff’s best evidence is DX-1, the raw Notamify text. Defendant agrees it carries the most weight. But read it carefully. A1010/26 and A1015/26 are airport-operations notices. They say airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports operating sunrise-to-sunset; prior permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights. They do not say the western Tehran FIR is closed. They do not close overflight routes. They do not identify airways, altitude blocks, or an FIR-wide suspension. They do not prove that commercial flights transiting the region were broadly suspended.\\n\\nPlaintiff asks the council to bridge that gap by inference: airport closures plus permission requirements should be treated as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions. But the competing inference is at least as strong: this was a partial, conditional airport restriction, with numerous operating airports and an approval path for civil IFR passenger service. PX-1’s limited-exception clause cannot erase PX-1’s partial-closure exclusion. A closure is not “broad” merely because it starts with the words “all airports” when the same operative text lists many operating exceptions and permits passenger flights with approval.\\n\\nDX-2 reinforces caution. It reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is consistent with a limited airport-activity suspension. It is not proof of a major airspace closure.\\n\\nThe evidentiary gaps also matter. There is no official Iranian CAA or ICAO artifact in the record, no airport movement data, no flight-tracking exhibit showing actual suspension, and no route or overflight closure record. PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary summaries; DX-1 is an aggregator capture. The council can credit them for the airport restriction they show, but should not inflate them into proof of facts they do not contain.\\n\\nPreponderance means more likely than not. The record makes it more likely that Iran imposed a significant, non-weather, permission-based restriction on western Iranian airport operations. It does not make it more likely that Iran initiated a major closure of its airspace or a major airspace region as PX-1 defines that term. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1: Market rule and arbitration proposition\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2: Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: The Indian Express, \\\"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- The subheadline states that only eight Iranian airports remained operational under daylight-only restrictions.\\n- The article reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX).\\n- It reports that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, citing Gulf News.\\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational: Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas.\\n- It states that even at those airports, flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- It reports flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor.\\n- The article characterizes the NOTAM as formalizing the most extensive restrictions in weeks amid non-weather military/diplomatic tensions.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3: Siasat corroborating report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\\nSource: Siasat.com, \\\"Iran closes western airspace amid reports of possible US military action\\\". By Sakina Fatima. Published May 23, 2026 8:33 am IST; updated May 23, 2026 9:44 am IST.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- The article reports that Iran imposed new airspace restrictions on Saturday, May 23, amid reports that the Trump administration was reviewing military options against Tehran.\\n- It identifies a Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, and reports that it announced the closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran Flight Information Region.\\n- It reports that only a limited number of facilities were permitted to operate during daylight hours.\\n- It states the restrictions were expected to remain in place until Monday, May 25, with airlines required to seek fresh approval from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority before operating passenger flights in affected areas.\\n- The article places the announcement amid heightened regional tensions and diplomatic activity, including U.S. contingency planning and Iran-related negotiations; it does not describe weather as the cause.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-Rule: market rule and proposition\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1: Notamify raw NOTAM text for A1010/26 and A1015/26\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2: Iran International report on official denial and exempted airport activity\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1: Raw NOTAM text confirms western Tehran FIR airport closures\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R2: Iran International confirms prior western-FIR airport suspension despite denying a new nationwide notice\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1: raw NOTAM text shows airport-operations restriction and operating exceptions\\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nVisible title/summary: \\\"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\\\"\\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\\nRaw NOTAM shown:\\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\\nOISR AND OIAM\\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2: official-denial report shows ambiguity and limited airport-suspension framing\\nSource: Iran International, \\\"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\\\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\\n- The spokesperson said: \\\"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\\\"\\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace closure, May 23 2026 (ev_6877e32e36e2_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-6877e32e36e2)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `6877e32e36e2b58bf10a9b2d917614c815931dc94d707627c69bb1fc195f509c`\\nBytes: 1524\\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, valid until May 25, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and limiting remaining airports to daylight operations with fresh per-flight CAA approval.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Siasat report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, May 23 2026 (ev_25136676d648_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-25136676d648)\\nSource: https://www.siasat.com/trump-considers-new-iran-strikes-as-diplomacy-enters-critical-phase-3475705/\\nSHA-256: `25136676d648360a3c4d2329f64e071677d51e8d2dc36aa30b7dbcf314121c79`\\nBytes: 1103\\nRelevance: Corroborates that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western Tehran FIR, with limited daylight operations and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights; describes non-weather military/diplomatic context.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw text for OIIX A1010/26 and replacement A1015/26 (ev_5e5109b5ca63_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-5e5109b5ca63)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 and https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\\nSHA-256: `5e5109b5ca632110b53c1e6f333fa92259a70d8b970b57de188d7b8dbcc1bce7`\\nBytes: 2376\\nRelevance: Shows the raw NOTAM wording available from a NOTAM aggregator. The text frames the measure as airport-operations closures in the west part of Tehran FIR, lists exceptions operating sunrise-to-sunset, requires new permission for civil IFR passenger flights, and shows A1015/26 replacing A1010/26 with a longer exception list before the deadline.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country (ev_6057a17cc5bf_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-6057a17cc5bf)\\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\\nSHA-256: `6057a17cc5bf9d03bc6a13a3f87c381c3974e116d8d6e2a3a9ecd39961ab6e61`\\nBytes: 1142\\nRelevance: Provides a contrary/source-chain complication: Iran's Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson reportedly denied a new official aviation notice imposing nationwide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while the same report acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nPlaintiff searched for the decisive source class: official Iranian aviation notice/NOTAM, source-specific public reports, and adverse material. The official NOTAM artifact was not obtained in this opportunity. The submitted reports identify the same NOTAM number, OIIX A1010/26, the same May 22-May 25 period, the same western Tehran FIR region, and the same daylight/per-flight approval restrictions. This is secondary-source proof, with a provenance limitation: PX-2 says the NOTAM detail was reported by Gulf News, and PX-3 independently reports the NOTAM but does not attach the official notice. Adverse check: defendant's partial-operation theory is supported by the reported continued operation of eight airports under daylight and fresh approval; plaintiff treats that as a limited-exception issue, not as proof of ordinary commercial availability.\\n\\n[defendant] Defendant source-chain and scope ledger\\nInspected all visible evidence with list/stat/read. Plaintiff evidence consists of secondary report captures; neither is the official NOTAM. Targeted searches for A1010/26 and contrary official-denial language found Notamify raw NOTAM pages and an Iran International report, both submitted as defendant evidence. The decisive unresolved gaps are the absence of an official CAA/ICAO source artifact, no admitted overflight or route-closure record, no airport movement data, and no proof of complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence read\\nPlaintiff read defendant's two new evidence items. The Notamify item states that all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except named sunrise-to-sunset airports, that all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and that new permission from CAA/Iran CAA was required for civil IFR passenger flights. The Iran International item denies a new nationwide/social-media notice but also acknowledges the earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with limited sunrise-to-sunset exemptions.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":885709,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":9},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":13,\"version\":13}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C1","after_version":13,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260630141638","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C1","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C1\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the proposition is not about whether a prediction market, UMA, or any platform governance process reached the right result. It asks a factual question under the market rule: by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, did Iran initiate a major non-weather closure of its airspace?\n\nThe current record contains one admitted case-packet item, ev_e61df84283cc_market-page. That packet proves the governing standard and the questions that will decide this case. A qualifying closure must be Iranian-initiated, not solely weather-related, and timely. It must also be major: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. The rule also draws two important lines. Limited cancellations, delays, or partial closures do not qualify. But limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure, such as flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not defeat qualification. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are not enough.\n\nThat admitted packet does not yet prove the occurrence facts. It does not itself establish that an Iranian aviation authority issued a specific May 22-May 25 closure, which airports were covered, whether commercial arrivals and departures were suspended, whether overflights were barred, or whether any exceptions were limited enough to preserve a broad closure. Those facts must be proved with source material, not assumption.\n\nPlaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The case will likely turn on whether the late-May Iranian aviation restrictions, if proved by official NOTAM or equivalent authority material and corroborated reporting, were a broad security-driven closure of a major Iranian airspace region rather than a mere localized delay or third-party avoidance. If the evidence shows Iran shut the western Tehran FIR or the airports within that region to ordinary commercial operations, while allowing only daylight operations or flights with fresh official approval, then the exception language matters: controlled permission for limited flights may be consistent with a qualifying broad closure.\n\nThe strongest opposing theory is also clear from the rule. Defendant will likely argue that the relevant May 24 condition failed because the restriction was only partial: some airports allegedly remained operational, some flights could proceed with approval, and the platform outcome for the May 24 market is listed as No. Those points deserve scrutiny, but none ends the factual inquiry by itself. The record standard is preponderance of the evidence, and the rule asks what Iran actually initiated, not what traders later priced or how a platform displayed its result.\n\nThe decisive proof should therefore be the source chain: the official Iranian aviation notice or NOTAM; its effective time, expiry time, affected FIR sector and airports; its treatment of commercial arrivals, departures, and transit; and credible reporting that confirms how the notice operated in practice. Equally important will be any contrary source showing that listed airports continued ordinary commercial arrivals and departures without a broad suspension, or that the restrictions were imposed by third parties rather than Iran.\n\nAt this opening stage, plaintiff asks the council to keep the dispute focused on those rule elements. If the evidence shows a broad, non-weather, Iranian-initiated regional closure by the deadline, limited official exceptions should not be allowed to turn a qualifying closure into a non-event. If the evidence instead shows only scattered delays or narrow localized restrictions, plaintiff will not have met the burden. The forthcoming record should decide that factual line.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the plaintiff bears the burden to prove the rule’s factual condition, not merely to point to tension in the region, airline caution, or market chatter. The current admitted record is narrow. The only evidence item is ev_e61df84283cc_market-page, a case-packet text file with the market metadata, rule text, examples, and arbitration notes. It establishes the legal test. It does not establish that Iran actually initiated a qualifying closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThat distinction matters. The rule does not resolve “Yes” for any aviation disruption in Iran. It requires a major, Iranian-initiated, non-weather closure. The case packet defines a major closure as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, generally applying across Iran or such a region. It separately provides that a complete non-weather suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports would qualify. But the same packet draws a limiting line: limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify. Third-party airline or foreign-government warnings are also insufficient.\n\nDefendant’s opening theory is therefore straightforward: this case should turn on exact scope, not labels. Plaintiff must produce the official Iranian aviation source, or a reliably captured equivalent source chain, showing what was closed, when it became effective, when it expired, which airspace or airports were covered, and whether commercial transit, arrivals, and departures were actually suspended broadly enough to meet the rule. A reference to “western airspace,” “airport restrictions,” or “approval required” is not self-proving. It could describe a broad qualifying regional closure; it could also describe a partial, conditional, or airport-specific restriction that the rule expressly excludes.\n\nThe packet itself identifies the right source classes: official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting. At this stage, none of that occurrence evidence is admitted. The record does not yet contain the NOTAM text, a Civil Aviation Organization notice, airport operational data, flight status records, or a complete chain showing that any reported restriction was official, timely, non-weather, and major within the rule’s terms.\n\nSeveral factual questions will decide the case. First, did Iran itself initiate the restriction, as opposed to airlines, foreign regulators, or risk advisories reacting to conflict? Second, did the restriction bar ordinary commercial overflight, arrivals, and departures across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region, or did it leave substantial commercial operations available by daylight, route, airport, or per-flight approval? Third, if plaintiff uses the listed-airport pathway, were commercial arrivals and departures completely suspended at at least two of IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, and IFN? Fourth, were any exceptions genuinely limited exceptions to a broad closure, or were they broad operating permissions that make the event partial rather than major?\n\nDefendant does not ask the council to decide now that no closure happened. The defendant asks the council to hold plaintiff to the rule. If later admitted evidence contains an official, authenticated notice proving a broad regional shutdown with only narrow exceptions, plaintiff may have a serious argument under the broad-region language. But if the evidence shows only partial airport closures, daylight operations, approval-based continued service, airline avoidance, or ambiguous secondary reporting without the official source text, the proposition should fail.\n\nThe current record proves the standard and the burden. It does not prove the event. Until plaintiff supplies the source chain and operational facts, the preponderance remains against finding that the May 24 market condition was satisfied.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the preponderance now favors the proposition.\n\nPX-1 supplies the rule. It asks whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited partial closures do not qualify, but limited exceptions to a broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nPX-2 and PX-3 supply the occurrence facts. PX-2 reports that Iran temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region, OIIX. It identifies the official act as Iranian Civil Aviation Authority NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, issued Friday, May 22, effective immediately and valid until May 25, ordering shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR. PX-2 further reports that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were restricted to daylight hours with fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority. PX-3 corroborates the same core facts: NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran FIR, only a limited number of facilities could operate in daylight, and airlines needed fresh Iranian CAA approval before passenger flights in affected areas.\n\nThose facts satisfy each element. First, initiation: both reports attribute the restriction to Iran's aviation authority through a specific NOTAM, not to airlines, foreign regulators, or market commentary. Second, timing: the reported NOTAM began May 22 and remained valid until May 25, so it was in force before the May 24 deadline. Third, non-weather cause: the reports place the measure in a security and military-diplomatic context, not weather. Fourth, magnitude: western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region, and the reported measure was not a scattered airport delay. It suspended civil flight permits in the western OIIX sector and shut all airports in the western part of that FIR.\n\nDefendant's best point is that some airports remained operational under daylight and fresh-approval limits. But that is not fatal under PX-1. The rule expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify the closure. A system in which ordinary civil flight permits in the western sector are suspended, airports in the western FIR are shut, and the remaining national operations require daylight timing and fresh official approval is not normal commercial availability. It is a broad Iranian-controlled suspension with limited permissions.\n\nPlaintiff does not need to prove the separate listed-airport pathway if the broad-major-region pathway is met. And that matters because PX-2 says several listed airports were among the eight still operating under restrictions. The better reading is therefore not that every listed airport was completely shut; it is that Iran closed a major airspace region and permitted only constrained exceptions elsewhere. That is exactly the distinction PX-1 preserves.\n\nThe proof is not perfect. The official NOTAM text itself is not in the record, and PX-2 appears to report the NOTAM detail through Gulf News. That limits weight. But preponderance does not require perfect custody where two admitted reports identify the same official notice number, same authority, same dates, same FIR, same closure of western-region airports, and same approval/daylight restrictions. No admitted contrary source shows the NOTAM was fake, weather-based, third-party-imposed, or merely a few isolated cancellations.\n\nOn this record, the more likely factual conclusion is that by May 24, Iran had initiated a non-weather broad closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the full argument record still does not prove the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nPX-1 is the controlling rule. It requires more than a disruption: Iran must initiate a non-weather “major closure” by the deadline. A major closure is a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The rule also has a separate listed-airport path: complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two named airports. It expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\n\nPlaintiff’s PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary reports, not the official NOTAM. They help identify a lead, but their own contents show why the lead is not enough. PX-2 says eight airports remained operational, including several listed in PX-1, and that those airports could operate in daylight with fresh per-flight CAA approval. PX-3 likewise describes closure of “airports” across the western section of the Tehran FIR, with a limited number of facilities permitted to operate during daylight and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights in affected areas. That is not proof of a complete suspension at two listed airports; it is the opposite.\n\nDX-1, the Notamify capture of the raw NOTAM text, is the most specific evidence now in the record. It narrows, rather than expands, plaintiff’s case. A1010/26 is categorized as AD Airport Operations and says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except specified airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. It does not say the Tehran FIR is closed to overflights. It does not identify ATS-route closures. It does not say commercial flights transiting Iranian airspace are suspended. It is an airport-operations NOTAM with named operating exceptions.\n\nDX-1 also shows that before the deadline A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 and expanded the exceptions. The replacement listed OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR, and OIAM as operational from sunrise to sunset, again with permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. OISS is Shiraz and OIFM is Isfahan; PX-2 also lists IKA, Mehrabad, Mashhad, Shiraz, and Isfahan among airports that remained operational in some form. On the listed-airport pathway, plaintiff has not shown complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two named airports.\n\nNor has plaintiff proved the broad-region pathway. The rule’s phrase is not merely “some airports in a region were restricted.” It requires broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The admitted raw text speaks in terms of airports in the west part of the FIR, and then carves out numerous operating airports. It permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. Plaintiff asks the council to treat that as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions, but the record equally, and more precisely, supports a partial airport restriction with substantial conditional operations.\n\nDX-2 adds a provenance and conflict problem. Iran International reported that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization denied a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule, while also acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is not a clean defense win, because it confirms some airport restrictions. But it defeats plaintiff’s attempt to turn two article summaries into a settled official source chain proving a countrywide or major-region airspace closure.\n\nThe source chain remains weak. No official Iranian CAA page, ICAO bulletin, original NOTAM feed record, airport movement record, or flight-data exhibit is admitted. PX-2 even attributes the key official-NOTAM claim to Gulf News rather than reproducing the underlying source. DX-1 is an aggregator capture, useful for text, but even that text supports conditional airport operations and does not prove overflight or route closure.\n\nThe plaintiff’s best point is the rule’s “limited exceptions” clause. But exceptions are limited only against an otherwise broad closure. The council cannot assume the predicate. Here the admitted evidence shows named airports operational, permissions available for civil IFR passenger flights, an expanded exception list before the deadline, and no admitted proof that commercial transit through a major airspace region was broadly suspended.\n\nOn this record, the proposition is not more likely true than false. The council should find that plaintiff proved a partial, conditional western-airport restriction, not a major non-weather closure of Iranian airspace within the market rule.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, defendant’s new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s case; it supplies the specificity defendant said was missing.\n\nDX-1 is now the most exact source in the record. Its raw A1010/26 text says: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating from sunrise to sunset; all previous permissions are suspended for all operators; new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. A1015/26 replaces A1010/26 and repeats the same structure: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except a listed set, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat is not ordinary commercial operation. It is a general closure in a defined major Iranian aviation region, with named exceptions and an official permission regime. PX-1 expressly anticipates this situation: limited exceptions to a broad closure, including flights pre-approved by Iranian civil aviation authorities, do not disqualify a closure.\n\nDefendant tries to make overflight-route closure the decisive test because DX-1 is categorized as airport operations and does not list ATS-route closures. But PX-1 does not require every route, altitude, or overflight track to be separately closed. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The west part of the Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region. Closing all airports in that west part, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is a broad suspension of commercial aviation in that region, especially as to arrivals and departures.\n\nDefendant is right that plaintiff should not lean on the separate listed-airport complete-suspension pathway. The stronger and sufficient pathway is the broad-major-region clause. The presence of exceptions, and even A1015’s expanded exception list, does not convert the measure into a few scattered delays. The operative rule distinguishes partial closures from broad closures with limited exceptions. DX-1’s phrase “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” is the language of a broad closure with exceptions.\n\nDX-2 is also narrower than defendant suggests. It denies a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and refers to a social-media notice. But the proposition does not require countrywide restrictions. More importantly, DX-2 acknowledges that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization had said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That confirms the core event; it only disputes an overbroad nationwide version.\n\nThe final factual line is therefore clear. If the rule required total nationwide shutdown or complete closure of two listed airports, defendant would have a stronger case. It does not. It allows a major-region closure and preserves limited official exceptions. On the admitted raw NOTAM text, Iran initiated a non-weather closure of the west part of the Tehran FIR by the deadline, suspended prior permissions for all operators, and allowed only constrained CAA-approved passenger operations. That meets the rule by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the sharpest issue: whether DX-1 shows a broad major-region closure with limited exceptions, or a partial airport-operations restriction. The record supports the latter.\n\nDefendant does not deny that DX-1 shows a real Iranian aviation restriction, in force before the deadline, in a non-weather context. The problem is scope. PX-1 does not count every Iranian aviation restriction. It requires a major closure: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It then separately counts complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Limited or partial closures do not qualify.\n\nDX-1’s raw text is precise. It is coded QFALC and presented as AD Airport Operations. It says all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except named airports that are operational from sunrise to sunset. It then says previous permissions are suspended and new permission must be requested for operation of civil IFR passenger flights. That is evidence about airport operations and permissioning. It is not evidence that the Tehran FIR, or the western part of it, was closed to commercial transit. It does not identify closed airways, closed overflight routes, an FIR-wide airspace closure, altitude restrictions, or a suspension of all commercial flights transiting the region.\n\nPlaintiff says the rule does not require every route or altitude to be listed. Fair enough. But plaintiff still must prove the thing the rule does require: a broad closure or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. The only raw text in evidence speaks in narrower airport terms and simultaneously permits civil IFR passenger operations at named airports with CAA permission.\n\nThe “limited exceptions” clause does not solve that gap. It protects a closure already shown to be broad; it does not transform a partial restriction into a broad closure. Here the exceptions are not incidental: A1010/26 listed eight operating airports, and A1015/26 expanded that list to twelve before the deadline. The record also shows listed market airports remained operational in some form. That defeats the separate complete-suspension pathway and reinforces the partial nature of the measure.\n\nDX-2 matters for the same reason. Plaintiff is right that it acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. But it also reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing restrictions on the country’s airspace and said flights were operating according to schedule. That conflict is not proof of “No” by itself; it is a warning against overreading an airport-activity suspension as a major airspace closure.\n\nAfter rebuttal, the decisive gap remains unchanged. The record proves restricted, permission-based airport operations in western Iran. It does not prove a broad suspension of commercial transit, arrivals, and departures through a major Iranian airspace region, and it does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports. Under the market rule’s own exclusion of partial closures, plaintiff has not carried the preponderance burden.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now gives you the precise source defendant said was missing: the raw NOTAM text. The proposition should be found true by a preponderance.\n\nStart with PX-1. The plaintiff does not have to prove total nationwide closure or complete suspension at two listed airports if the broad-region pathway is satisfied. PX-1 defines a major closure to include a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region, and it expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe decisive record evidence is the NOTAM text in DX-1, read with the corroborating reports in PX-2 and PX-3. A1010/26, effective May 22 and valid past the May 24 deadline, states that all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports operating sunrise-to-sunset. It also states that all previous permissions are suspended for all operators and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for civil IFR passenger flights. A1015/26 replaced A1010/26 before the deadline, expanded the exception list, but kept the same core command: all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports, prior permissions are suspended for all operators, and new Iran CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n\nThat is an Iranian-initiated, non-weather aviation restriction in force before the deadline. The non-weather context is supported by PX-2, PX-3, and even the framing of DX-2; no record evidence suggests weather. The restriction was imposed through Iran CAA/CAO channels. It applied to the west part of the Tehran FIR, a major Iranian aviation region. It closed all airports in that region except named ones and converted ordinary civil IFR passenger operations into daylight, permission-based exceptions.\n\nDefendant’s best point is that DX-1 is coded as airport operations and does not separately list closed overflight routes, airways, or altitudes. But PX-1 does not require a total FIR route closure. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in the region. Commercial flights arrive and depart through airports. When all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except specified daylight airports, all previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and every civil IFR passenger flight needs fresh CAA approval, commercial arrivals and departures in that major region are broadly suspended.\n\nDefendant’s other point is that the exceptions are too numerous. That would matter if the rule treated every exception as fatal. It does not. The question is whether the record shows a broad closure with limited exceptions or merely scattered delays. The text “all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed except...” answers that question. It is a general closure first, with exceptions second. The fresh-permission requirement confirms that the exceptions were controlled permissions, not normal operations.\n\nDX-2 does not change the result. It denies a new nationwide or social-media notice and says flights were generally operating according to plan. But it also acknowledges the earlier Friday statement that activity at airports in the western Tehran FIR had been suspended until Monday, with only limited airports allowed to operate sunrise-to-sunset. That is not a denial of plaintiff’s actual theory. Plaintiff’s theory is not nationwide closure; it is major-region closure.\n\nThe record is imperfect in provenance because the official Iranian source page is not before you, and Notamify is an aggregator. But the preponderance standard asks what is more likely. The raw NOTAM text, two corroborating reports, and even defendant’s contrary article all converge on the same core fact: by May 24, Iran had suspended ordinary airport activity in the west part of the Tehran FIR and allowed only constrained, permission-based civil passenger operations at named airports.\n\nUnder PX-1, that is a major non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the question is not whether Iran imposed a real aviation restriction. It did. The question is whether plaintiff proved a major closure within PX-1’s specific market rule. On this record, that burden is not met.\n\nPX-1 is demanding in two ways. It requires a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. Alternatively, it requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. And it expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures.\n\nThe listed-airport pathway is gone. PX-2 itself says several listed airports remained operational under restrictions. DX-1’s replacement NOTAM A1015/26 includes additional operating exceptions, including OISS and OIFM. Whether those operations were daylight-only and permission-based, they were not a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports.\n\nThat leaves only the broad-region pathway. Plaintiff’s best evidence is DX-1, the raw Notamify text. Defendant agrees it carries the most weight. But read it carefully. A1010/26 and A1015/26 are airport-operations notices. They say airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR are closed except named airports operating sunrise-to-sunset; prior permissions are suspended; new CAA permission is required for civil IFR passenger flights. They do not say the western Tehran FIR is closed. They do not close overflight routes. They do not identify airways, altitude blocks, or an FIR-wide suspension. They do not prove that commercial flights transiting the region were broadly suspended.\n\nPlaintiff asks the council to bridge that gap by inference: airport closures plus permission requirements should be treated as a broad regional airspace closure with limited exceptions. But the competing inference is at least as strong: this was a partial, conditional airport restriction, with numerous operating airports and an approval path for civil IFR passenger service. PX-1’s limited-exception clause cannot erase PX-1’s partial-closure exclusion. A closure is not “broad” merely because it starts with the words “all airports” when the same operative text lists many operating exceptions and permits passenger flights with approval.\n\nDX-2 reinforces caution. It reports that Iran’s aviation authority denied a new official notice imposing countrywide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while acknowledging an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions. That is consistent with a limited airport-activity suspension. It is not proof of a major airspace closure.\n\nThe evidentiary gaps also matter. There is no official Iranian CAA or ICAO artifact in the record, no airport movement data, no flight-tracking exhibit showing actual suspension, and no route or overflight closure record. PX-2 and PX-3 are secondary summaries; DX-1 is an aggregator capture. The council can credit them for the airport restriction they show, but should not inflate them into proof of facts they do not contain.\n\nPreponderance means more likely than not. The record makes it more likely that Iran imposed a significant, non-weather, permission-based restriction on western Iranian airport operations. It does not make it more likely that Iran initiated a major closure of its airspace or a major airspace region as PX-1 defines that term. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1: Market rule and arbitration proposition\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2: Indian Express report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: The Indian Express, \"Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\". By Express Global Desk. Published May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- The subheadline states that only eight Iranian airports remained operational under daylight-only restrictions.\n- The article reports that Iran temporarily closed airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX).\n- It reports that the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, citing Gulf News.\n- It states that only eight airports across the country remained operational: Tehran Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini International, Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad, and Bandar Abbas.\n- It states that even at those airports, flights were restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines had to obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\n- It reports flight-tracking data showed commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor.\n- The article characterizes the NOTAM as formalizing the most extensive restrictions in weeks amid non-weather military/diplomatic tensions.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3: Siasat corroborating report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26\nSource: Siasat.com, \"Iran closes western airspace amid reports of possible US military action\". By Sakina Fatima. Published May 23, 2026 8:33 am IST; updated May 23, 2026 9:44 am IST.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- The article reports that Iran imposed new airspace restrictions on Saturday, May 23, amid reports that the Trump administration was reviewing military options against Tehran.\n- It identifies a Notice to Air Missions (NOTAM), OIIX A1010/26, and reports that it announced the closure of airports across the western section of the Tehran Flight Information Region.\n- It reports that only a limited number of facilities were permitted to operate during daylight hours.\n- It states the restrictions were expected to remain in place until Monday, May 25, with airlines required to seek fresh approval from Iran's Civil Aviation Authority before operating passenger flights in affected areas.\n- The article places the announcement amid heightened regional tensions and diplomatic activity, including U.S. contingency planning and Iran-related negotiations; it does not describe weather as the cause.\n\n[defendant] DX-Rule: market rule and proposition\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-1: Notamify raw NOTAM text for A1010/26 and A1015/26\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nVisible title/summary: \"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nVisible title/summary: \"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\nOISR AND OIAM\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\n\n[defendant] DX-2: Iran International report on official denial and exempted airport activity\nSource: Iran International, \"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson said: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1: Raw NOTAM text confirms western Tehran FIR airport closures\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nVisible title/summary: \"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nVisible title/summary: \"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\nOISR AND OIAM\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R2: Iran International confirms prior western-FIR airport suspension despite denying a new nationwide notice\nSource: Iran International, \"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson said: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1: raw NOTAM text shows airport-operations restriction and operating exceptions\nSource 1: Notamify page, OIIX A1010/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nVisible title/summary: \"All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nSource 2: Notamify page, OIIX A1015/26. URL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nVisible title/summary: \"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\"\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30. Category shown: AD Airport Operations.\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\nOISR AND OIAM\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2: official-denial report shows ambiguity and limited airport-suspension framing\nSource: Iran International, \"Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country.\" Published May 23, 2026, 10:32 GMT+1.\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said it had issued no new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal.\n- The organization's spokesperson said flights were continuing according to schedule.\n- The spokesperson said: \"Conditions in the country's airspace remain as before, and flights are operating according to plan.\"\n- Without giving details of the notice to airmen, or NOTAM, the spokesperson denied a notice recently circulated on social media.\n- The denial came after Iran's Civil Aviation Organization said Friday that activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate.\n- That earlier notice said several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express report on Iran western airspace closure, May 23 2026 (ev_6877e32e36e2_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-6877e32e36e2)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `6877e32e36e2b58bf10a9b2d917614c815931dc94d707627c69bb1fc195f509c`\nBytes: 1524\nRelevance: Reports that Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, valid until May 25, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and limiting remaining airports to daylight operations with fresh per-flight CAA approval.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Siasat report on NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, May 23 2026 (ev_25136676d648_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-25136676d648)\nSource: https://www.siasat.com/trump-considers-new-iran-strikes-as-diplomacy-enters-critical-phase-3475705/\nSHA-256: `25136676d648360a3c4d2329f64e071677d51e8d2dc36aa30b7dbcf314121c79`\nBytes: 1103\nRelevance: Corroborates that NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 announced closure of airports across the western Tehran FIR, with limited daylight operations and fresh CAA approval for passenger flights; describes non-weather military/diplomatic context.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw text for OIIX A1010/26 and replacement A1015/26 (ev_5e5109b5ca63_submitted-evidence-03-defendant-5e5109b5ca63)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269 and https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nSHA-256: `5e5109b5ca632110b53c1e6f333fa92259a70d8b970b57de188d7b8dbcc1bce7`\nBytes: 2376\nRelevance: Shows the raw NOTAM wording available from a NOTAM aggregator. The text frames the measure as airport-operations closures in the west part of Tehran FIR, lists exceptions operating sunrise-to-sunset, requires new permission for civil IFR passenger flights, and shows A1015/26 replacing A1010/26 with a longer exception list before the deadline.\n\n[defendant arguments] Iran International report: Iran denies new NOTAM limiting flights across country (ev_6057a17cc5bf_submitted-evidence-04-defendant-6057a17cc5bf)\nSource: https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605239595\nSHA-256: `6057a17cc5bf9d03bc6a13a3f87c381c3974e116d8d6e2a3a9ecd39961ab6e61`\nBytes: 1142\nRelevance: Provides a contrary/source-chain complication: Iran's Civil Aviation Organization spokesperson reportedly denied a new official aviation notice imposing nationwide airspace restrictions and said flights were operating according to schedule, while the same report acknowledges an earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with exemptions.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nPlaintiff searched for the decisive source class: official Iranian aviation notice/NOTAM, source-specific public reports, and adverse material. The official NOTAM artifact was not obtained in this opportunity. The submitted reports identify the same NOTAM number, OIIX A1010/26, the same May 22-May 25 period, the same western Tehran FIR region, and the same daylight/per-flight approval restrictions. This is secondary-source proof, with a provenance limitation: PX-2 says the NOTAM detail was reported by Gulf News, and PX-3 independently reports the NOTAM but does not attach the official notice. Adverse check: defendant's partial-operation theory is supported by the reported continued operation of eight airports under daylight and fresh approval; plaintiff treats that as a limited-exception issue, not as proof of ordinary commercial availability.\n\n[defendant] Defendant source-chain and scope ledger\nInspected all visible evidence with list/stat/read. Plaintiff evidence consists of secondary report captures; neither is the official NOTAM. Targeted searches for A1010/26 and contrary official-denial language found Notamify raw NOTAM pages and an Iran International report, both submitted as defendant evidence. The decisive unresolved gaps are the absence of an official CAA/ICAO source artifact, no admitted overflight or route-closure record, no airport movement data, and no proof of complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence read\nPlaintiff read defendant's two new evidence items. The Notamify item states that all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR were closed except named sunrise-to-sunset airports, that all previous permissions were suspended for all operators, and that new permission from CAA/Iran CAA was required for civil IFR passenger flights. The Iran International item denies a new nationwide/social-media notice but also acknowledges the earlier western-Tehran-FIR airport activity suspension with limited sunrise-to-sunset exemptions.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C1","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C1","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":885709,"role_id":"council","turn_number":9},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":13,"version":13}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782830086928},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to review the case details and the submitted evidence to make a decision. Let's identify the key evidence and the rule.\n\nThe case is about whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by May 24, 2026 by 11:59 PM ET.\n\nThe rule (PX-1/DX-Rule) states that a \"major closure\" means:\n- A broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, or\n- A non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN), and\n- With the understanding that limited exceptions to a broad closure (like per-flight approvals) don't disqualify it.\n\nThe relevant evidence:\n1. Plaintiff's evidence (PX-2, PX-3): Reports from Indian Express and Siasat stating that Iran issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, closing the western part of Tehran FIR to civil flights, with only 8 airports operational during daylight hours with fresh CAA approval required for passenger flights.\n\n2. Defendant's evidence (DX-1): Raw NOTAM text from Notamify showing:\n   - A1010/26: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD EXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET...\"\n   - A1015/26 (replacement): \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD EXCEPT: OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR AND OIAM...\" (more airports added)\n\n3. Defendant's evidence (DX-2): IRAN International report stating:\n   - Iran's Civil Aviation Organization denied issuing \"a new official aviation notice imposing restrictions on the country's airspace and that flight conditions remained normal\"\n   - BUT also acknowledged \"activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate\"\n\nKey considerations:\n- The rule doesn't require a countrywide closure, just a major Iranian airspace region.\n- The Tehran FIR (Flight Information Region) is a major Iranian airspace region.\n- The NOTAM clearly states \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\" (with some exceptions).\n- The exceptions are described as \"operational from sunrise to sunset with fresh CAA permission\" for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- According to the rule, \"limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting.\"\n\nThe raw NOTAM text shows:\n- A broad suspension (\"all airports in west part of Tehran FIR are closed\")\n- With exceptions for specific airports that can operate only under restricted conditions (daylight hours with new permission)\n\nThis meets the definition of a \"major closure\" with limited exceptions that don't disqualify it per the rule.\n\nThe Iran International report (DX-2) does deny a \"new nationwide\" notice and claims flights are \"normal\", but it simultaneously acknowledges the \"western part of Tehran FIR\" airport activity was suspended \"with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate\".\n\nThe evidence does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports (e.g., IKA, THR, etc.), but it does prove a major regional closure of the western Tehran FIR with limited exceptions.\n\nConclusion:\nThe raw NOTAM text provides clear evidence of a broad closure in a major Iranian airspace region (western Tehran FIR) with limited exceptions to the closure in certain airports. The rule explicitly states limited exceptions don't defeat a broad closure.\n\nSo I should vote \"demonstrated\" because the evidence shows Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region with limited exceptions that don't disqualify it.\n\nMy rationale: \"The raw NOTAM text confirms a broad closure of western Tehran FIR airports with specific exceptions that operate under limited daylight hours and fresh approval requirements, which meets the rule's definition of a major closure with permissible limited exceptions.\"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ea3bac8bacea443aaf81f5","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The raw NOTAM text confirms a broad closure of western Tehran FIR with specific exceptions operating under limited daylight hours and fresh approval requirements, which meets the rule's definition of a major closure with permissible limited exceptions.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":18811,"output":1009,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19820,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782830086931,"responseId":"gen-1782830087-5naWeFrqnDM1B7yuCc3l","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_ea3bac8bacea443aaf81f5","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C1\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260630141638\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nremaining_ms: 877348\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260630141638\",\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":877348,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":9}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C1\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260630141638\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C1\nremaining_ms: 877348\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260630141638\",\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C1\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":877348,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":9}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260630141638","member_id":"C1","ok":true,"result":{"text":"Council vote accepted."},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":true,"deadline":"2026-06-30T14:49:32.63373867Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C1","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C1","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":877348,"role_id":"council","turn_number":9}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"submit_council_vote"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782830095287},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, the user provided a detailed case scenario where I need to act as council member C1 for a specific arbitration case. Let me go through the steps they mentioned.\n\nFirst, the task was to use the MCP tool to call AAR tools with the correct format. The initial step was to call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` with empty args. The response showed \"state: ready\", so then I needed to read the prompt and other details to decide on the vote.\n\nThe prompt included a proposition about whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by May 24, 2026. The rule states a \"major closure\" must be a broad closure of flights in Iranian airspace or a major region, excluding limited partial closures but allowing limited exceptions for pre-approved flights.\n\nLooking at the evidence: The plaintiff submitted PX-2 and PX-3 as reports about the NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 and A1015/26. The defendant provided DX-1 with the raw NOTAM text from Notamify and DX-2 from Iran International. The raw NOTAM shows that all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed except those operating sunrise-to-sunset with new CAA approval required for passenger flights. The Iran International report mentions denial of a nationwide notice but acknowledges the western region suspension with limited exceptions.\n\nThe key issue is whether this constitutes a broad regional closure with limited exceptions as per the rule. The rule's examples include the April 2024 western Iran closure as qualifying. The NOTAM text states closures except specific airports operating with permissions, which the rule explicitly says doesn't disqualify the closure because exceptions are permitted. The plaintiff argues it meets the broad-region pathway, while the defense claims it's a partial restriction.\n\nMy role is to decide based on preponderance of evidence. The raw NOTAM from DX-1 is the most specific evidence and does match the rule's description: a broad closure with limited exceptions (daylight-only operations under approval). The rule's wording says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure... will not disqualify such a closure.\" So even with some airports open under restrictions, this is still a qualified major closure.\n\nTherefore, the vote should be \"demonstrated\" because the evidence shows a broad closure in the western Tehran FIR region with permissible exceptions, meeting the rule's criteria. The rationale needs to be concise: mention the raw NOTAM confirming the closure with specific exceptions that fit under allowed limited exceptions.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"The raw NOTAM text confirms a broad closure of western Tehran FIR with specific exceptions operating under limited daylight hours and fresh approval requirements, which meets the rule's definition of a major closure with permissible limited exceptions."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":19120,"output":559,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19679,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782830095287,"responseId":"gen-1782830095-7BTab7rPHwrQU3N3EQ2g","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}],"willRetry":false}
